article.description: U of the Pacific 76, San Jose State 65
article.headline: U of the Pacific 76, San Jose State 65
article.linkText: U of the Pacific 76, San Jose State 65
article.story: STOCKTON, Calif. (AP) -- Christian Maraker scored 14 points to lead the University of the Pacific to defeat San Jose State 76-65 in overtime Friday night in the season opener for both teams. Junior center Tyler Newton scored six of his 11 points in overtime, including a transition basket to start the extra stanza and a breakaway dunk in the final seconds. Pacific ended the 151st meeting between the Northern California rivals with a 15-4 run. The team made all eight of its free throws in overtime. Guards Miah Davis and David Doubley each scored 12 points and Newton and Guillaume Yango had 11 points for the Tigers. Yango added a game-high 11 rebounds as Pacific held a 46-33 advantage on the boards. Michael McFadden came off the bench to lead San Jose State with 15 points, including the 3-pointer that sent the game into overtime tied at 61-61. Brett Lilly had 13 points for the Spartans and center Eric Walton had eight points and 10 rebounds. A Newton basket and a 3-pointer by Doubley began the overtime scoring and gave Pacific a lead it never would relinquish. The Tigers were 8-of-8 from the line in the final two minutes and 20-of-24 for the game. A seesaw second half featured 13 lead changes and six ties before McFadden's 3-pointer with 48 seconds remaining tied the game for the final time at 61-61. Maraker's turnover with 22 seconds to play gave San Jose State an opportunity to win in regulation. But after the Spartans worked down the clock, Demetrius Brown missed a point-blank bank shot at the buzzer to send the game into an extra period.
